				<p><p>In this case, you can think of a "channel" as a "linear control" -- a single-dimensional value.  For example, throttle can go from 0%-100% (or -100% to 100% if you're doing some really crazy things); roll, pitch, and yaw are expressed as a range of degrees.</p>

<p>The RC transmitter you refer to has 2 joysticks, each with 2 dimensions, for a total of 4 channels that can be controlled -- this covers all the channels you mentioned.</p>

<p>However, since a quadcopter can move freely in any cardinal direction, you need only transmit 3 channels: throttle, roll, and pitch.  This prevents you from controlling what direction the quadcopter is facing at any one time, but does not limit its mobility.  </p>
</p><br>
